column12: For the next 5 minutes, please recall a time when you performed these acts of kindness for someone else. Examples include cooking dinner for friends or family, doing a chore for a family member, paying for someone's coffee in line behind you, visiting an elderly relative, or writing a thank you letter. Briefly summarize the kind act you did, and who the act was for. Finally, as you write, don't worry about perfect grammar and spelling, and remember that anything you write will remain strictly confidential. Should an experimenter read this entry in the future, it will be identifiable only by a participant number and not by a name.

column12: paid for lunch with a friend, complimented some of my friends on their appearance, called my mom and talked to her and told her i loved her

Today my friend and I decided to go to Coffee Bean after class to get a beverage. We were coming out linguistics and headed over to Coffee Bean when a girl fell over because she was wearing high heals . I came over and I helped her get up when no one else did. After that I invited the girl to Coffee Bean with us and paid for her drink in order to make her feel better about herself. This is something that I commonly would not do.

Yesterday one of my hall mate was transferring boxes into his car. I was getting back from my classes and I saw him struggling with taking his things downstairs. I saw some of my hall mates just past by him and not even try to any contact with him. There was a gut feeling that was telling me to help him out. Once I asked his eyes lit up. Who would of that one simple task can bring someone so much joy.

This Christmas I wrote my sister a short story as a Christmas gift as I currently don't have a job. She has been my sounding board as I decided what career I wanted to pursue and is always there to listen, so when I decided I wanted to go back to the first idea I'd had for a story, I decided it should be for her. During the process, we were in the middle of a major move, so I completed the majority of the writing between the hours of 11pm and 1am.

My mom was having a particularly bad day after the move, so we went out for Starbucks and I paid for her beverage.

My mom has gone through three ankle surgeries in the past two years, and is still in the recovery process. Her ankle often gets tired, so I massage it daily for her.

My sister enjoys me doing her hair, so I do so daily.

My dad recently suffered an injury to his eye, so I have been reminding him to take his medicine as well as administering the drops every now and again.

My uncles came down during the break, so we took them on a little tour of Riverside, and took them to lunch.

Today I was helping a peer of mine understand a concept of chemistry. I saw her struggling before class, therefore, I sat down with her and asked her a series of questions to know what was wrong. After a saw the problem she was facing I explained to her what she has to do and how she can further understand the concept. 
Also besides helping that peer throughout the whole day, I made it my duty to hold the door for anybody that was coming behind me. It is a small act of kindness but it's nice to hold the door for somebody once in a while it may just make their day it shows that you care.

1. I bought a nice birthday gift for my friend (something he mentioned he wanted)
2. I helped my friend lock up her workplace
3. I helped my mom run errands
Today, instead of deciding to hang out with my boyfriend, I stayed home while my parents were at work. I cooked rice, did the laundry for them and helped them fill out various utility bills.

I remember one time, I looked for my friends dog when she ran away. We looked everywhere and asked neighbors if they had seen her. Eventually after about an hour and a half of looking we found her in a nearby park running around with another dog. When we saw her, she immediately ran towards us and took her home.

The last time I did an act of kindness for someone was offering food to the people in my hall. Last week, I saw a homeless person on the street and I bought him food. Earlier today, my friend Stephanie was going through a hard time and I let her talk to me about it and I offered her some advice to help her with her situation.

I cook dinner for my family all the time when I lived at home. I would make breakfast for my brothers periodically and also for my boyfriend at the time. I buy food for homeless people, and I would clean the house so my parents would not have to have a big mess to come home to after work. I like doing acts of kindness for people all the time because I was raised that way.

Today I helped a young lady find her class in the psychology building. Seeing her so relieved as she found her class and was not late, made me feel really good. I felt like I made a difference. 
Later within the day, I helped an older man put his groceries in his car. He thanked me and smiled, which brought me joy. 
Lastly, I helped my mom study for her Coding Licenses exam. She seemed relieved as she had someone to study with, I was happy to oblige.

The act of kindness I did was for my mother. Since today is Friday, I was picked up from school to spend the weekend at home. We are from Orange County, and our house is a good hour and a half drive not accounting for traffic. Because it was getting late and I worried about traffic, I offered to drive home so she could rest. Even though there was traffic and it was aggravating to drive in, it was worth it to give my mom a break in her life.

I drove my younger brother to school the last day of break because he was going to be late. I cooked dinner for my brother and a friend who came over. I also kept our house clean when my parents were gone.

The last time I performed one of these acts of kindness was when I went home and I helped my mom with chores around the house. I helped her clean the floors, vacuum, and do laundry. I also helped her a little with cooking dinner.

Today in the morning after class two of my classmates were speaking about how they found a student ID but none of them where able to drop it of at the hub. As I was leaving and overheard this I told them that I would not be doing anything after class and that I would take the ID in so they would not have to miss any of their obligations.

1. Today I bought lunch for my friend Oscar.
2. I helped teach someone who was new at work.
3. I have rides home to my friends off campus.

Three days ago I had new neighbors moving and they had a uhaul truck full of heavy furniture and clearly they were not going to be able to carry all of it on their own. I saw them struggling and they were about to spend 100 dollars just to call someone to help them move everything inside. I decided to come out and help them move everything and get settled in.

I purchased Girl Scout cookies and walked over to give them to a group of girls sitting at a table on campus. On the way to school, I gave a homeless man a few dollars. On my cell phone, I sent a lengthy text message to a friend from high school thanking her for being a wonderful friend to me.

An act of kindness I did was buy my little sister a pair of pants. My family doesn_验t have money to freely spend on clothes and she has been wearing the same few pants for a while and as I was buying myself some pants I decided it would be a nice gesture to buy a pair for her. I felt good doing it because she was happy afterwards because she now has a new pair of crisp jeans.

Over break, I went to my great-aunt's nursing home in Sunnyvale. I drove down from San Francisco with the intentions of simply spending the day with her.  When I got there, she was sleeping.  Not wanting to wake her up, I sat down in her room and read until she woke up.  After she woke up, we sat and had an amazing conversation.  I then took her out for dinner and we spent the rest of the day together.
I helped my friend reorginize her closet, and then we took the clothes to the donation center.

During winter break, I decided to buy small gifts for my friends at UCR. I didn't tell them that I was buying them gifts, or gave any hints. It was sort of an appreciation/Christmas gift for helping me throughout the quarters, both spiritually and academically. When we all came back from the break, I gave them the gifts along with a hopeful note to do well again this winter quarter. It's extremely nice to see their joyful reactions.

I remember one time I had gone to dinner with my girlfriend and we were enjoying a nice meal, afterwards before leaving I ordered an extra plate of food for her grandparents. We then drove to their place and surprised them with a meal since they haven't eaten the whole day. They were extremely happy and gave both my girlfriend and I a huge hug. I had also paid for a friends movie ticket since he  forgot his wallet and could.t purchase the ticket himself.

I try to be a good person and spread kindness as i can, but I cannot remember a random act of kindness big enough that it is memorable. I have cooked for others, done work on behalf of others, visited relatives, and wrote countless thank you letters but it was not that big of a deal? For example, when I wrote my counselor a thank you letter, it was not necessarily a random act of kindness. He had helped me tremendously and it was a simple thank you for all his effort.

The most recent thing that I've done for people close to me that I can recall is make dinner for my family. This happened about a week ago before I came back to UCR for this quarter. I enjoy cooking so doing it for other people never feels like that substantial of a sacrifice. When it comes to strangers the only things that come to mind are small acts like holding the door or letting someone go ahead of me in a line when they're in a hurry.
The act I did was go to the store before going over to my friends house and buying his mom her favorite box of chocolates to surprise her with them.
I did chores around the house for my mother who was under a lot of stress
I bought my friend a book that he has wanted for a long time, but never was able to get because he never had enough money, or because of some other circumstance.
I remember deciding to cook for my family every now and then simply because I want to do something nice for them.  They are always busy so that Thursday, I decided to simply home cook a meal

This morning I cooked breakfast for my sick friend as she could not get out of bed to get food for herself. I also went to  nearby convenience store to acquire some medications for her. Later in the day, I paid for my friend's grocery as he happened to be short few dollars.

I_验m currently an employee at Nordstrom Rack and within the Rack, we have different departments that specialize in different things. I work in the Service Experience where I_验m responsible for checking customers out. One time, a customer approached me and asked if I can look up a price for an item. Typically, I would call the women_验s department, but this time I went out of my way and did it for them
I sat and listened to my friend as she talked about some of the dificulties she was having with her current boyfriend.
I bought some chocolate eggs for my younger siblings from work.

During the summer volunteering, I created cards of kindness for patients to receive on their food trays when it was time for their meals and I created them because it was for word of encouragement since they are in the hospital majority of their time.

The kind act that I performed today was giving money to a homeless person for food. He was in a wheelchair as he asked me for 30 cents. Rather than giving him a few cents, I gave him 5 dollars. He thanked me and said _岩God bless you_.

Today I paid for my sister's boba at a milk tea shop. We were both going to just buy our separate bobas but since we were going to get the same thing anyways I just bought both together, as she picked me up from the train station. I also wrote thank you letters to my closest friends from high school saying how much I appreciate them now. And when I had a bunch of left over food, I just gave it my friends who got out of lecture late and didn't have time to grab food, so I just gave them my food instead so they could be on time for their next class.

During middle school, my family and I went to OC on a trip to do some shopping and run some errands. As I was walking into the store, I realized an elderly woman standing outside having some difficulty pushing her shopping cart off a bumper while another car was about to move into a parking spot where the shopping cart was blocking. Quickly, I left my family and ran to help her. The lady was so grateful to me afterwards and I will never forget my first time helping a stranger.

a random act of kindness that i once did was take care of s sick friend. i took her to the doctor & bought her her medications. i made sure she wasn_验t missing anything , bought her food & made her teas. i was there until she felt 100% better.

Last week while I was with my family, I made brownies for everyone in my family. They all enjoyed it and they also appreciated me for making it.I made brownies because I wanted them to feel happy before I left for college.

A couple days ago I took charge around the house and helped out with most of the chores that had to be done for the week. Both my parents were at work so I was the only one to get everything done. I played some music and in a few hours I finished all the house work and it felt nice to greet both my parents with a clean house. They were able to relax over the weekend.

An act of kindness that I performed most recently was during my winter break. I cleaned the house and cooked dinner. My parents were working so I made sure they came to a clean home and meal. I performed this everyday for the three weeks of winter break. I wanted them to have one less task to worry about after they had long days at work.

I confess that acts of kindness come not too often.  But when something -- the mood, I suppose -- strikes me, I take it upon myself to do something for another.  Last week I paid for someone's toll both entry.  Now I have no idea who that person behind me was, and they certainly had not the foggiest idea who I was.  And I was able to spare a bit of money, so I figured: why not?  True, I find myself asking how such an act benefits me, but I then proceed to forget about it.  That is, however, until a survey forces me to dig up the memory in question.

The other day my best friend and I were grabbing a bite to eat at an In-N-Out near Disneyland. We were just about done when I noticed that a woman with her three kids were struggling to find a table since the place was packed. I got up without saying a word to my best friend and walked up to the lady to tell her we would be leaving soon and could have her take the table. She seemed very surprised that I went out of my way for her and her children and just thanked me about three times saying that what I had done was very thoughtful and nice. My best friend said that the reason she thanked me so much was that with our society nowadays people are selfish and don't do those types of thing out of the kindness in their hearts. Honestly I didn't see the big deal.
Yesterday I cooked dinner for my family, I helped a friend in need, I did something special for my friends birthday, and cleaned the house for my mom.

Today I went to visit my grandpa in OC, I hadn't seen him in a few weeks so it was great to finally see him again!I also helped around the house, cleaned my room and and my closet - it was good to finally have things in order.

Recently I cooked soup for my family
Recently I cleaned the house
A few months ago a homeless man lived by the corner of my house. To ease his hunger and thirst, I made him a sandwich, brought him two bottles of waters, and gave him 5 dollars for his next meal.

Today, I took the time to cook breakfast for my mother. My mom who normally wakes up earlier than everyone else usually cooks the family breakfast. Instead I woke up about 2 hours than I normally would and cooked her her favorite meal in bed.

I remember making breakfast for my brother I just decided to make myself breakfast one day and thought that I might as well as make a separate dish for my brother. Another time I transported a fresh rose from my home to school to give to this one girl at school fro Valentines. Finally I recall giving my mom money as on offering of gratefulness for her after I finished working during the summer.
My act of kindness for the day was for me to thank everybody who I came across, for example, the cashier at Starbucks for his service. I also paid for somebody else's meal when I was at McDonald's

It was my 17th birthday and I was in my Junior year of High School. I always spent my birthday with my friends as I would call all my friends for dinner at my house and then we would play a few games and then everyone would happily leave. However, this time I thought of making it a bit different by not just celebrating my happiness with my family and friends, whereas by creating a positive difference in the lives of other people and making them happy. I am privileged to be born in a good family and I have never felt short of anything as my family is financially stable. On this birthday, I went to an orphanage and decided to cut my cake with my other people in the orphanage. I felt very happy seeing them smile and I am lucky to have made so many good friends in that orphanage. This birthday was one of my best birthdays till date and it is very special to me.

I had a few friends throughout my lifetime try to end their life at some point in their lives, anyone from my bestfriends or people I didnt fully know but I was still there for them, I gave them my emotional, physical and mental support whenever I could, I would check up on them and their wellbeing and ensure them that whatever they had going on right now it wasnt the end of the world

One time when I performed an act of kindness would be working for a non-profit organization that provided meals that would be directly dropped off to the homes of the elderly. I have now worked at this organization for 2 summers- my junior and senior year in high school, and I am planning on working for them again this summer (2018).

As I am taking the survey right now, I just spent my afternoon doing dishes and mowing the lawn for my family members. Instead of seeing it as a "kind act," I see it as a responsibility that I should be doing, since I am a part of the family.  I feel some people often take what their family members do for them for granted, and they think chores naturally belong to someone (usually the mother). I don't know if "cooking dinner for friends and family, doing a chore for a family member, visiting an elderly relative" are "kind acts."
A kind act I did was helping an old lady get to her home. It was very windy and and cold. I saw her struggling to walk straight and helped her.

I cooked a lunch for my family to show them that I appreciate what they do for me. I mainly did it for my mom because she is usually busy and tired, but still cooks all our meals. I felt proud and kind to do the favor for my mom.

I remember a time back in high school, my friend had dropped a weight on his toe and it fractured his toe completely. As a result he was restricted to crutches for a couple of months and he had trouble moving about on the campus. So I took it upon myself to talk to administration to see if they would allow me to be his helper and help him carry his things and help him just overall.
I invited some of my friends to a dinner that I cooked.

An act of kindness I tend to do is volunteer a lot towards helping children with disabilities to play soccer. I_验ve always done it for myself because I enjoy helping others. Although I did use some of the hours for community service (because high school makes hours of community service a requirement), I_验d turn some hours in but I did it for them. It would make me really happy to see their smiles light up when they can score a goal. It makes me happy bc I see them do things and overcome what people think they wouldn_验t be able to do.
The past week, I cooked dinner for my friends at home. I figured they did not have anymore groceries, therefore I surprised them by making tacos for dinner.

An act of kindness I have done is give my 85 year-old grandfather a pedicure. My grandfather loves tending to his garden in the backyard, which he does so quite frequently. This usually results in him having very dirty toenails as he likes to wear open-toed sandals while gardening. With this, I give him a pedicure whenever I see that his nails have gotten too dirty so he can enjoy freshly new nails. I scrub out all the dirt from his nails, cut them if they are too long, and add a thin layer of natural coating to ensure protection for his brittle nails.

My friends and I were going on band tour and I decided that I was going to bake them cookies so that they would have something to enjoy on the bus as we drove up to northern California (six hour bus ride). I made a bunch of cookies so that everyone would have plenty to eat and I made a variety so that there would be a cookie flavor for everyone to enjoy.
Every now and then, I would help my mother around the house by mopping the floors or doing the dishes.

The last time I performed an act of kindness was when I unwillingly cleaned up after my cousin's birthday party after the party was over. After the party of course when everyone was leaving, they all left a mess as would any party, however I decided it was nice to lend a helping hand so my aunt and uncle would not deal with the struggles a party offers when it is done.

On January 12, I complimented my friend who has a low self esteem. I also saved a seat for a friend who was running late to class and proceeded to take notes for him while he arrived. For the third kind thing I did was help someone read a menu at the Denny's Diner where I work at.
I wrote a thank you letter for my neighbor, gave my friend a laundry basket because he forgot his at home, and called up my friend to let her rant to me about a problem she had.

I recently paid for my friends drinks and snacks at the movie theaters, because they did not have anymore money so I paid for anything they wanted to eat and drink, because I know that my friend would do the same if I were in his position.
I took the time to peer review a friend's personal statement letters for college.

When I was in high school, I always would help people with mathematics on Tuesday mornings even when I had my own homework lined up to do. Even though some of the people I knew didn't really appreciate me, I would still do whatever I could to help them and make sure they understood the topic and would be able to do future problems on their own. I would always put aside what I needed to help whoever needed the help. I would usually help a friend of mine named Gurbir, who essentially really only wanted me to help him in math more so than he was my friend to be there for my mental and emotional support as I was dealing with the stress of college applications and my multiple AP classes.

I cooked breakfast, lunch, and dinner for my boyfriend, I did his laundry and cleaned the apartment we both inhabit. I also helped my friend push her car last night when her battery suddenly died. I let someone go in front of me in line this morning to get their coffee because they seemed in a rush. I made lunch again for my boyfriend to take to work. I also went grocery shopping and bought food for him as well as myself even though he has a job and I don't. I walked my friend to her internship because she was nervous.

I help my mother clean the house because she works six out of the seven days, Sunday being her only day off and working 12 hours straight every day. It is the little I can do for my mom because I know how hard she works. I wash and put away the dishes, broom the entire house and mop it as well. I also, wash the clothes and out hers and mine away so there is nothing left out. There was another time, where I gave a girl my apple because she had not eaten all day and she was about to pass out. I was walking to my seat when she fell in front of me and I asked her if she was okay. I then asked her if she had eaten and she faintly told me she did not, so I gave her my apple and she said thank you and I said you are welcome and that was the last I saw of her.

An instance where I performed an act of kindness for someone was for my grandfather. I cooked him lunch and fed it to him because he was unable to feed himself since he has dementia. I cooked him a meal enriched with high fiber and protein that would give him the proper nutrition. Feeding my grandpa required a lot of patience because he is very slow and old. However, feeding my grandpa made me happy.

Some acts of kindness I did for today was first, I helped my mom around the house by washing the dishes and taking out the trash. I also held the door open for other students as they were leaving the classroom and lastly I helped a coworker by taking a shift.

Sometimes, I believe my kindness takes over my life, and permits others to walk all over me. However, there was a single instance in which I truly felt as though I had an impact. 

There is a homeless man who resides by the exit of the freeway near my house. I see him nearly every day. There was one day, where I happened to know that it was James' birthday (this man's name is James). I waved hi, and drove past him. I drove to the nearest Jack-in-the-Box, and bought him a meal. I bought him a chicken sandwich, with some large fries and a large coke. I also bought him a small chocolate cake, since it was his birthday and all. I drove into the freeway again to deliver this small present to James. He was so happy and pleased, and at that point in my life, I realized it doesn't matter who you are or what you do. What matters is your impact; I realized the impact I had on James. He is now my friend.
I only performed one act of kindness and that was opening the door for someone at school.

I called my sick grandma who I haven't talked to a while. I was nice to my dad by texting him back. I told my mom I was proud of her accomplishments. I took my mom to the movies. I write positive messages for my roomate. I am positive with my friends, I make fin activities to do together. I cooked for my mom and cleaned teh hosue. I wrapped presents for people. I baby sat and helped people move. I helped someone on the computer.

one act of kindness I did was cook dinner for my friends and family. I've cooked food for my friends several times because I told them I could cook good so they wanted to see me cook and taste my food. I cooked the food and they really liked it so this was one of my random acts of kindness.

After I got home from class today, I remembered that my mom needed some milk from the grocery store, so I got back in my car and went to the grocery store to get milk. It wasn't all that special, really, but it's nothing something that I'd usually do; normally, I just crash at home. After that, I swept up the bathroom floor for my mom as well. We've got most of our cat-related items in there, including the litterbox, so there tends to be litter on the floor from time to time.

Acts of  kindness are important to me because being kind as a small act can make somebody_验s whole day better. I like to wash up plates for my mother after cooking dinner, ironing my dad_验s shirts, giving my sisters rides, randomly visiting other family and friends, holding the door open for anyone, picking things up with people drop something and always checking up on people and asking them how their day has been. These things may seem a little and dispensable but it_验s the small things that add up to the big message

I would not consider it much an act of kindness, if not something I am supposed to do. I clean my parents home every Monday and Friday. Granted I live here, I do it because i feel the need to do it, despite living with 4 male siblings, I am the only one who does it.

The first act of kindness that I did today was let someone know that their backpack was opened and offered to close it for them. I noticed this when I was walking back from class and he was in front of me. So I told him that it was opened and offered to close it for him. The second act was when I returned to my apartment complex. As I opened the gate to my apartment complex I held it open for others to enter and exit before I. And the last act that I did was complement someone on their look and wished them a good day. I told a classmate after class that her look was good and that I hoped she had a good day.
after class, i told a girl her opinions mattered in a class in which the majority's opinions are opposite to hers; i agree with her opinions. she was being ridiculed during class by a classmate

An act of kindness that I did for someone else was washing the dishes for my mother when she fell asleep on the couch or when there was too much in the sink. My mother works and comes home around dinner time and prepares dinner. She leaves the dishes as the last thing to do, but sometimes she falls asleep on the couch and when I come downstairs and see this, I decide to wash all the dishes and clean around the kitchen so she doesn't have to wash them when she wakes up. Another time this occurred was when there are too much items in the sink so I decide to wash it so there is space.
The kind act that I did was donate money to my ex-best friend's mom who was diagnosed with breast cancer.
I wrote a thank you note for one of my friends because he always helps me with math homework when I don't understand it. In the note, I expressed my appreciation for everything he does for me.
Last Friday, I invited and drove a few of my pledge brothers to petsmart and Target to get groceries and supplies and we had a lot of fun.
I took my family out to dinner once

1) I bought my boyfriend a snack and iced tea when he had a long day of classes
2) I brought a blanket for my friend Hannah  because she was cold
3) I cleaned the bathroom for my mom when she was busy

Today, I helped point out other people in my lab section's mistakes before it became a problem that would result in them having to restart the experiment. I also showed my brother around my school campus and treated him to some dinner.
